unittitle.value: John B. Snook Architectural Record Collection

abstract.label: Abstract
abstract.value: The collection is comprised of ca. 2500 architectural drawings by John Butler Snook and his various firms.

p.value: Photocopying undertaken by staff only. Limited to twenty exposures of stable, unbound material per day. See guidelines in Print Room for details.
This collection should be cited as: John B. Snook Architectural Record Collection, PR 064, Department of Prints, Photographs, and Architectural Collections, The New-York Historical Society.

In 1836 Snook married Maria A. Weekes, with whom he had nine children that lived to adulthood. Three of these, James H., Samuel B., and Edward T., eventually joined his practice, which was renamed John B. Snook & Sons. One of Snook's sons-in-law, John W. Boylston, also worked in the firm. Snook died at his home in Brooklyn in 1901.

The John B. Snook Architectural Records Collection spans the period from 1843 to 1948 and contains architectural drawings and record books from John Butler Snook and his descendents' careers as architects in New York City. The collection is divided into two series: Architectural Drawings and Record Books.

Series I: Architectural Drawings Scope and Contents note

Series I. Architectural Drawings contains a total of 2,719 drawings representing 225 different projects. Drawings include elevations, plans, sections, mechanical and engineering drawings, blueprints, working drawings, and presentation drawings. The majority of the projects found here are buildings in New York City and surrounding boroughs and towns. Most projects represented are generally those from later in Snook's career. A few projects date from the time of John Snook Sons, the firm's name after Snook's death. Snook's design for the original Grand Central Terminal is only represented here by one large elevation, probably a presentation drawing.

Projects are arranged by size of drawing, and are numbered accordingly for easy reference. The numbers were assigned by the N-YHS staff and do not reflect any intention on the part of the architect. All drawings for the same project are rolled together, unless some of the drawings required flat storage. A list of projects by geographical location, and by date, follow this finding aid.

The architectural drawings were surveyed and inventoried in the summer of 2004. Those that could not be unrolled were humidified and flattened. Remaining rolled drawings are extremely fragile and may need conservation before being viewed. Please contact the Print Room staff at least one week before anticipated visit. Also, the collection was not processed per se, as there remains a great deal of research to be done on each building.

 Series II: Financial Records Scope and Contents note

Series II. Business Records includes 37 bound volumes, all but one are some form of financial and business records. One bound "Index to drawings by John B, Snook and John B. Snook & Sons" lists projects and drawings, but it can be difficult to match these to the projects for which drawings are available.
